<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-439-040  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 439 040.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>The Wall Street Journal  July 20 1989 pB6(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Computer virus security issue is cited by GAO. (General AccountingOffice)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Davis, Bob.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The absence of centralized control over the US research computernetwork and a disregard of security measures were partlyresponsible for the 1988 computer virus which affected 6,000systems, according to a report from the General Accounting Office.andO;Because no single government agency is responsible for networksecurity, the Internet computer network is particularly vulnerableto viruses.andP;  Universities and laboratories that use Internet andthat detected the virus had no one to report it to, and they didnot know how to stop it.andP;  The GAO recommends that the coordinationof security arrangements for Internet should be the responsibilityof the White House Science Advisor's office.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     United States. General Accounting OfficeSecurityComputer VirusesNetworksLegal IssuesGovernment AgencyColleges and UniversitiesUnited States. Congress. House. Subcommittee on TelecommunicationsInternet (Computer network)United States. Office of Science and Technology Policy.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>